choices.text:
finding clarity

They tend to tell the truth, or how they see something; consequently, Armenians are not good actors. I spent all my teen years climbing a force fed religious and military pill addiction into my brain demanding the impossible – to be sane.

On an after school hike with my friend, I heard gunshots, not a minute later I started hearing screams, by the time I reached the military barracks a man was dragged with bound hands, upon interrogation, we found out that he was the grandfather of the current Armenian prime minister's bodyguard. We questioned the guard and offered the poor old man to fake his death, let the guards feel better, and put him through a medical test to save him from the cruel guard. There was more physical violence in the cavalry.

Back to the story. Armenians don't know how to forgive; even the elderly group. As the younger generation travel to America, some of our family members came to live here in person; I wonder how would a normal person react to that. I am so large-hearted to learn to let go. I've tried to move forward and now I have made a self-discovery that Armenia steals my happiness, it represses my personal journey; it makes me emotionally and mentally unstable.

Armenians generally don't eat on time. It feels like you wake up to a gun and not a coffee, have a bickering with the government, then you wish if you had a coffee to calm you down,
